The algorithm is as follows:

1.  For each item, calculate its "gravity" as follows:
    a.  If the item is new, its gravity is 1.
    b.  If the item is old, its gravity is 0.
    c.  If the item is popular, its gravity is 1.
    d.  If the item is unpopular, its gravity is 0.
2.  Rank the items based on their gravity.
3.  The items with the highest gravity are ranked first.

Here's an example of how this algorithm would work in C#:

```csharp
public class Item
{
    public DateTime CreatedAt { get; set; }
    public int Popularity { get; set; }
}

public class GravityAlgorithm
{
    public static List<Item> RankItems(List<Item> items)
    {
        items.Sort((x, y) =>
        {
            if (x.CreatedAt > y.CreatedAt)
            {
                return -1;
            }
            else if (x.CreatedAt < y.CreatedAt)
            {
                return 1;
            }
            else
            {
                if (x.Popularity > y.Popularity)
                {
                    return -1;
                }
                else if (x.Popularity < y.Popularity)
                {
                    return 1;
                }
                else
                {
                    return 0;
                }
            }
        });

        return items;
    }
}
```

This code defines a class `Item` with properties for the item's creation date and popularity. It also defines a class `GravityAlgorithm` with a method `RankItems` that takes a list of items and returns a sorted list of items based on their gravity.

The `RankItems` method sorts the items based on their creation date and popularity. If two items have the same creation date, the item with the higher popularity is ranked higher. If two items have the same creation date and popularity, they are ranked equally.

This algorithm assumes that new items are more important than old items, and popular items are more important than unpopular items. You can adjust the weights of these factors as needed.
